## Results  

### Constituency vote  

The first‑past‑the‑post contests produced the following vote totals and seat allocations:

| Party | Constituency votes | % of total | Seats won | Change |
|-------|-------------------|-----------|-----------|--------|
| [Liberal Democratic Party](/Liberal_Democratic_Party_(Japan)) | 21,836,096 | 38.63 % (+2.01 pp) | 239 | +16 |
| [New Frontier Party](/New_Frontier_Party_(Japan)) | 15,812,326 | 27.97 % (+2.56 pp) | 156 | –4 |
| [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(Japan,_1996)) | 6,001,666 | 10.62 % (new) | 52 | +52 |
| Others & Independents | 7,730,832 | 13.68 % | 53 | –11 |

The overall turnout stood at 59.65 % of the 97,680,719 registered voters, marking a decline of 7.61 percentage points from the previous election.

### Party‑list (proportional) vote  

When the separate party‑list vote was aggregated, the distribution of seats more closely mirrored national vote shares:

| Party | Proportional votes | % of total | Seats won (PR) | Total seats (constituency + PR) |
|-------|-------------------|-----------|----------------|---------------------------------|
| [Liberal Democratic Party](/Liberal_Democratic_Party_(Japan)) | 18,205,955 | 32.76 % | 70 | 169 |
| [New Frontier Party](/New_Frontier_Party_(Japan)) | 15,580,053 | 28.04 % | 60 | 96 |
| [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(Japan,_1996)) | 8,949,190 | 16.10 % | 35 | 17 |
| [Japanese Communist Party](/Japanese_Communist_Party) | 7,268,743 | 13.08 % | 24 | 24 |
| [Social Democratic Party](/Social_Democratic_Party_(Japan)) | 3,547,240 | 6.38 % | 11 | 11 |
| [New Party Sakigake](/New_Party_Sakigake) | 582,093 | 1.05 % | 0 | 2 |
| Others | 1,417,077 | 2.55 % | 0 | 0 |

The final composition of the [House of Representatives](/House_of_Representatives_(Japan)) therefore consisted of 256 seats for the governing coalition (LDP + SDP + NPS) and 235 seats for the opposition bloc, giving the coalition a comfortable majority.

### Geographic distribution  

The vote‑strength map revealed pronounced regional patterns. The LDP dominated the urban and industrial heartlands of Kantō, Kansai and Chūbu, while the NFP found pockets of strength in the Chūgoku and Shikoku blocks. The DP’s support was concentrated in the urban prefectures of Tokyo and Kanagawa, whereas the JCP and SDP retained traditional strongholds in the rural prefectures of Tōhoku and Hokkaidō. The proportional‑representation allocation further amplified the geographic spread of smaller parties, ensuring that even regions with low constituency vote densities could influence the composition of the Diet through the party‑list tier.

